1
00:00:36,345 --> 00:00:39,548
<i>Sometimes, Dr Lecter and I</i>
<i>would talk...</i>

2
00:00:39,640 --> 00:00:41,633
<i>when things got quiet enough...</i>

3
00:00:41,725 --> 00:00:43,802
<i>about the science courses</i>
<i>I was takin'.</i>

4
00:00:43,894 --> 00:00:47,762
<i>Some kind of mail-order courses</i>
<i>in psychology, Nurse Barney?</i>

5
00:00:47,857 --> 00:00:49,267
<i>No, sir.</i>

6
00:00:49,358 --> 00:00:52,229
<i>I don't consider psychology</i>
<i>a science...</i>

7
00:00:52,320 --> 00:00:54,893
<i>and neither did Dr Lecter.</i>

8
00:00:57,616 --> 00:00:59,158
<i>Now, Barney...</i>

9
00:00:59,242 --> 00:01:01,780
<i>while you were working</i>
<i>at the asylum...</i>

10
00:01:01,870 --> 00:01:07,908
<i>you observed Clarice Starling</i>
<i>and Hannibal Lecter interacting.</i>

11
00:01:08,001 --> 00:01:09,709
Interacting?

12
00:01:09,795 --> 00:01:12,546
Talking to one another.

13
00:01:12,631 --> 00:01:15,418
Yes.
Yes, it seemed to me that they...

14
00:01:15,509 --> 00:01:19,044
I can see you're eager to justify
your consulting fee...

15
00:01:19,137 --> 00:01:22,304
but why don't we start
with what you saw...

16
00:01:22,391 --> 00:01:24,430
not what you thought about
what you saw?

17
00:01:24,518 --> 00:01:28,979
Cordell, don't be like that.
Barney can give us his opinion.

18
00:01:29,064 --> 00:01:33,275
Barney, give us your opinion
of what you saw.

19
00:01:33,359 --> 00:01:35,767
What was it between them?

20
00:01:37,113 --> 00:01:41,277
Most of the time, Dr Lecter
didn't respond at all to visitors.

21
00:01:41,367 --> 00:01:44,203
He'd just, for instance,
open his eyes long enough...

22
00:01:44,287 --> 00:01:47,454
to insult some academic
who was there to look over him.

23
00:01:49,000 --> 00:01:51,621
With Starling,
he answered her questions.

24
00:01:51,711 --> 00:01:55,495
She interested him.
She intrigued him.

25
00:01:55,590 --> 00:01:59,089
He thought she was charming
and amusing.

26
00:02:00,011 --> 00:02:02,965
So Clarice Starling
and Hannibal Lecter...

27
00:02:03,056 --> 00:02:05,974
became friendly.

28
00:02:06,059 --> 00:02:09,973
Inside a kind of formal structure,
yes.

29
00:02:10,063 --> 00:02:13,312
And he was fond of her.

30
00:02:15,651 --> 00:02:17,858
Yes.

31
00:02:17,945 --> 00:02:19,226
Thank you, Barney.

32
00:02:19,322 --> 00:02:21,314
Thank you very much
for your candour.

33
00:02:21,407 --> 00:02:24,693
And keep all those wonderful items...

34
00:02:24,785 --> 00:02:27,490
from your personal Lecter
treasure trove coming.

35
00:02:27,580 --> 00:02:29,371
I've enjoyed them immensely.

36
00:02:29,457 --> 00:02:31,165
Mr Verger.

37
00:02:31,250 --> 00:02:33,788
Oh, I almost forgot.

38
00:02:33,878 --> 00:02:36,547
I might be able to get a cookie down.
What do you say, Cordell?

39
00:02:36,631 --> 00:02:39,086
I think it would kill you.

40
00:02:47,725 --> 00:02:50,642
- How much?
- Two hundred and fifty.

41
00:02:50,727 --> 00:02:52,519
Thousand.

42
00:02:54,273 --> 00:02:58,484
Cut a cheque for $250,000.

43
00:04:52,556 --> 00:04:54,964
How can she sleep
at a time like this?

44
00:04:56,435 --> 00:04:59,306
She's on a jump-out squad all night.
She's saving her strength.

45
00:05:29,092 --> 00:05:32,627
We got some guy named Bolton
from the DC Police.

46
00:05:33,972 --> 00:05:36,926
All right, everyone.
Pay attention. Here's the layout.

47
00:05:37,017 --> 00:05:39,591
Excuse me.
I'm Officer Bolton, DC Police.

48
00:05:39,687 --> 00:05:42,142
I can see that from your badge.
How do you do?

49
00:05:42,231 --> 00:05:43,725
I'm in charge here.

50
00:05:43,816 --> 00:05:46,022
Officer Bolton,
I'm Special Agent Starling.

51
00:05:46,110 --> 00:05:48,268
Just so we don't get off
on the wrong foot...

52
00:05:48,362 --> 00:05:50,520
let me explain
why we're all here.

53
00:05:50,614 --> 00:05:54,742
I'm here because I know Evelda Drumgo.
I arrested her twice on RICO warrants.

54
00:05:54,827 --> 00:05:57,448
DEA and ATF, in addition
to backing me up...

55
00:05:57,538 --> 00:05:59,530
are here for the drugs
and the weapons.

56
00:05:59,622 --> 00:06:02,540
You're here because our mayor
wants to appear tough on drugs...

57
00:06:02,626 --> 00:06:04,867
especially after his own
cocaine conviction...

58
00:06:04,961 --> 00:06:07,713
and hopes he can accomplish that
by having you join us here today.

59
00:06:08,632 --> 00:06:10,838
You got a smart mouth, lady.

60
00:06:10,926 --> 00:06:14,377
If you wouldn't mind, I'd appreciate it
if you'd let me continue.

61
00:06:15,722 --> 00:06:17,715
All right, take a look.

62
00:06:17,808 --> 00:06:20,762
Fish market.
Back's on the water.

63
00:06:20,852 --> 00:06:23,141
Across the street, ground floor,
is the meth lab.

64
00:06:23,230 --> 00:06:25,637
Evelda Drumgo's HIV positive.

65
00:06:25,732 --> 00:06:29,101
She will spit and bite if cornered,
so you should watch it.

66
00:06:29,194 --> 00:06:32,029
If you happen to be the one
who puts her in a patrol car...

67
00:06:32,114 --> 00:06:35,068
in front of the news cameras, Bolton,
you don't wanna push her head down.

68
00:06:35,159 --> 00:06:37,483
She'll likely have a needle
in her hair.

69
00:06:37,577 --> 00:06:40,364
<i>We want to take her inside the building,</i>
<i>not out in the street.</i>

70
00:06:40,455 --> 00:06:42,447
<i>We can get closest with the van.</i>

71
00:06:42,540 --> 00:06:45,624
<i>If it looks good, on my signal</i>
<i>we hit the front, DEA hits the back...</i>

72
00:06:45,710 --> 00:06:47,703
<i>DCPD backin'them up.</i>

73
00:06:47,795 --> 00:06:50,002
<i>She'll have her watchers out</i>
<i>at least three blocks around.</i>

74
00:06:50,965 --> 00:06:54,417
<i>They've tipped her before in time, so</i>
<i>let's not make spectacles of ourselves.</i>

75
00:07:06,481 --> 00:07:09,019
- Pretty busy today.
- I agree.

76
00:07:15,739 --> 00:07:17,613
Can I please get
a cup of coffee?

77
00:07:34,383 --> 00:07:36,672
- Did you see that?
- That's a roger.

78
00:07:45,353 --> 00:07:46,812
What's up, man?

79
00:07:56,822 --> 00:07:58,197
Goddam it. It's her.

80
00:07:58,282 --> 00:08:00,523
With three guys.
They're all packin'.

81
00:08:00,617 --> 00:08:03,535
She's carryin' something.
She's got a baby.

82
00:08:03,620 --> 00:08:07,036
<i>Hey, Brigham, it's too crowded.</i>

83
00:08:07,124 --> 00:08:09,282
<i>There are too many people.</i>
<i>I say we call it off.</i>

84
00:08:09,376 --> 00:08:10,574
What do you say?

85
00:08:10,669 --> 00:08:12,709
<i>I agree.</i>

86
00:08:12,796 --> 00:08:15,122
All units, stand down.

87
00:08:15,215 --> 00:08:17,422
- Whisky team copies.
- Burke copy.

88
00:08:17,509 --> 00:08:19,383
This is Bolton.
Stay on target.

89
00:08:19,470 --> 00:08:22,175
I said all units stand down, Bolton,
right now.

90
00:08:22,264 --> 00:08:24,387
<i>- It's too late. We're movin'in.</i>
- Bolton, he said it's off.

91
00:08:24,475 --> 00:08:26,218
Stand down now.

92
00:08:26,310 --> 00:08:28,303
She's carrying a baby.
I repeat, she's carrying a baby.

93
00:08:28,395 --> 00:08:30,850
All units stand down.

94
00:08:30,939 --> 00:08:32,978
<i>- Keep that gun down, Bolton.</i>
- Damn, dude got a piece.

95
00:08:33,066 --> 00:08:34,809
- Light his ass up.
- It's a go!

96
00:08:34,901 --> 00:08:36,395
FBI! Down on the ground!

97
00:09:18,695 --> 00:09:20,403
Hold it!

98
00:09:20,488 --> 00:09:22,481
Hold your fire!

99
00:09:24,492 --> 00:09:25,821
Don't!

100
00:09:28,830 --> 00:09:31,321
Evelda, get out of the car!

101
00:09:33,126 --> 00:09:34,834
Starling, is that you?

102
00:09:36,963 --> 00:09:39,086
Step away from the car!

103
00:09:40,675 --> 00:09:42,798
Show me your hands, Evelda.

104
00:09:44,512 --> 00:09:47,596
Please.
Show me your hands.

105
00:09:47,681 --> 00:09:49,259
How've you been?

106
00:09:49,350 --> 00:09:51,058
Don't do this.

107
00:09:51,143 --> 00:09:52,222
Do what?

108
00:10:24,509 --> 00:10:26,751
It's all right. It's okay.

109
00:10:26,845 --> 00:10:29,799
I know, I know. Baby, I know.

110
00:10:29,890 --> 00:10:32,345
It's okay.

111
00:10:32,434 --> 00:10:34,676
It's okay.

112
00:10:35,812 --> 00:10:37,805
It's all right.

113
00:10:56,584 --> 00:10:58,909
<i>Friends, family and coworkers</i>
<i>gathered here this morning...</i>

114
00:10:59,003 --> 00:11:03,130
<i>at Arlington National Cemetery</i>
<i>to bury BA TF Agent John Brigham...</i>

115
00:11:03,214 --> 00:11:06,548
<i>shot and killed in the line of duty</i>
<i>Friday. He was 40 years old.</i>

116
00:11:06,634 --> 00:11:09,920
<i>This ill-fated drug raid that claimed</i>
<i>his life and five others...</i>

117
00:11:10,013 --> 00:11:12,586
<i>is the latest in a seemingly</i>
<i>endless series of incidents...</i>

118
00:11:12,682 --> 00:11:14,474
<i>beginning with Waco, Texas...</i>

119
00:11:14,559 --> 00:11:17,893
<i>in which theJustice Department</i>
<i>and the FBI have been questioned...</i>

120
00:11:17,979 --> 00:11:20,850
<i>about their use of firepower</i>
<i>rather than judgment.</i>

121
00:11:20,941 --> 00:11:23,610
<i>This time it was FBI</i>
<i>Special Agent Clarice Starling...</i>

122
00:11:23,693 --> 00:11:25,437
<i>heading up</i>
<i>the calamitous strike force.</i>

123
00:11:25,529 --> 00:11:29,111
<i>Agent Starling attained some measure</i>
<i>of celebrity ten years ago...</i>

124
00:11:29,199 --> 00:11:32,533
<i>when she was given information</i>
<i>by Dr Hannibal "The Cannibal"Lecter...</i>

125
00:11:32,619 --> 00:11:34,778
<i>which led to the rescue</i>
<i>of Catherine Martin...</i>

126
00:11:34,871 --> 00:11:37,244
<i>daughter of the former US senator</i>
<i>from Tennessee.</i>

127
00:11:37,332 --> 00:11:41,115
<i>When she returns to work this week,</i>
<i>she won't be so celebrated.</i>

128
00:11:41,210 --> 00:11:44,164
<i>Attorney Telford Higgins, representing</i>
<i>one of the families of those slain...</i>

129
00:11:44,255 --> 00:11:47,007
<i>says he will file</i>
<i>a wrongful-death suit.</i>

130
00:11:48,426 --> 00:11:50,217
Cordell!

131
00:12:02,065 --> 00:12:04,935
- Yes, sir.
- Get me the justice Department.

132
00:12:12,742 --> 00:12:14,534
<i>Agent Starling?</i>

133
00:12:14,619 --> 00:12:18,367
<i>This is John Eldridge from DEA.</i>
<i>Assistant Director Noonan, you know.</i>

134
00:12:18,455 --> 00:12:21,575
Larkin Wayne from our Office
of Professional Responsibility.

135
00:12:21,667 --> 00:12:23,660
Bob Sneed, ATF.

136
00:12:23,752 --> 00:12:26,919
Benny Holcombe, assistant to the mayor.
And Paul Krendler.

137
00:12:27,006 --> 00:12:29,544
You know Paul.
Paul's come over from justice...

138
00:12:29,633 --> 00:12:32,124
unofficially,
as a favour to us.

139
00:12:32,219 --> 00:12:34,757
In other words, he's here,
and he's not here.

140
00:12:37,725 --> 00:12:40,761
So I take it you've seen the coverage
in the papers and on television?

141
00:12:40,853 --> 00:12:43,427
I have nothing to do with the news,
Mr Krendler.

142
00:12:43,522 --> 00:12:46,310
The woman had a baby in her arms.

143
00:12:46,400 --> 00:12:49,401
There are pictures. You could
see the problem, I would think.

144
00:12:49,487 --> 00:12:52,772
Not in her arms.
In a carrier across her chest.

145
00:12:52,865 --> 00:12:55,024
In her arms she had a MAC-10.

146
00:12:55,118 --> 00:12:58,201
Look, we're here to help you,
Starling.

147
00:12:58,286 --> 00:13:01,287
It's gonna be a hell of a lot harder
to do with a combative attitude.

148
00:13:06,420 --> 00:13:08,958
Can I speak freely, Mr Pearsall?

149
00:13:10,632 --> 00:13:13,717
Your agency called this office to get me
assigned to help you on this raid.

150
00:13:13,802 --> 00:13:15,759
I tried to do that.

151
00:13:15,846 --> 00:13:18,847
I clearly expressed my judgment
and was ignored.

152
00:13:18,932 --> 00:13:22,017
And now a good agent and a friend
is dead.

153
00:13:25,147 --> 00:13:27,720
You shot and killed five people
out there, Agent Starling.

154
00:13:27,816 --> 00:13:30,023
Is that how you define
good judgment?

155
00:13:30,945 --> 00:13:33,068
This raid was an ugly mess.

156
00:13:33,155 --> 00:13:36,274
I ended up in a position
where I had a choice of dying...

157
00:13:36,366 --> 00:13:38,358
or shooting a woman
carrying a child.

158
00:13:38,451 --> 00:13:40,693
I chose.

159
00:13:40,787 --> 00:13:42,447
I shot her.

160
00:13:43,373 --> 00:13:45,864
I killed a mother
holding her child.

161
00:13:47,961 --> 00:13:50,452
And I regret it.
I resent myself for it.

162
00:13:50,547 --> 00:13:53,038
Gentlemen, I'm going
to call a halt to this meeting...

163
00:13:53,133 --> 00:13:55,540
and get back to you individually
by phone.

164
00:13:59,931 --> 00:14:01,924
That was a waste of time.

165
00:14:03,685 --> 00:14:06,010
You have a secret admirer, Starling.

166
00:14:06,104 --> 00:14:09,687
He isn't much to look at,
but he does have friends in high places.

167
00:14:10,776 --> 00:14:13,610
Remember Mason Verger?

168
00:14:13,694 --> 00:14:16,268
Lecter's fourth victim.

169
00:14:16,364 --> 00:14:17,858
The rich one.

170
00:14:17,949 --> 00:14:20,356
The only one that survived.

171
00:14:21,536 --> 00:14:24,157
He says he has some new information
on Lecter he'll only share with you.

172
00:14:24,247 --> 00:14:27,865
What do you mean, only share it with me?
You want it, seize it.

173
00:14:27,959 --> 00:14:31,126
- I'd rather not.
- I wasn't speaking to you.

174
00:14:31,212 --> 00:14:33,703
When I speak to you, you'll know it
because I'll look at you.

175
00:14:35,466 --> 00:14:36,961
Why would we rather not?

176
00:14:37,051 --> 00:14:40,670
The last time he called was when we took
Lecter off the Ten Most Wanted List.

177
00:14:41,806 --> 00:14:44,262
He was upset about that.
We said, "Hey, that's life."

178
00:14:44,350 --> 00:14:47,684
<i>He said, "This is a Senate</i>
<i>Oversight Committee...</i>

179
00:14:47,771 --> 00:14:49,347
<i>to make your life miserable. "</i>

180
00:14:49,438 --> 00:14:52,439
His family's political contributions
may not be enough...

181
00:14:52,524 --> 00:14:54,232
to buy a senator...

182
00:14:54,318 --> 00:14:56,311
but they are enough
to rent them from time to time.

183
00:14:57,154 --> 00:15:00,772
There's no reason to go through that
if he really does have something new.

184
00:15:02,827 --> 00:15:06,824
<i>It's a good deal for you, Starling.</i>
<i>You can't pretend it isn't.</i>

185
00:15:08,124 --> 00:15:10,200
<i>Get to go back</i>
<i>on a celebrated case.</i>

186
00:15:10,292 --> 00:15:13,661
I'll take care of the media
for your Drumgo killing.

187
00:15:13,754 --> 00:15:15,130
Everyone's gonna be happy.

188
00:15:15,214 --> 00:15:18,298
I'm not happy.

189
00:15:18,384 --> 00:15:21,171
Well, maybe you're incapable
of being happy.

190
00:15:22,221 --> 00:15:24,344
Mr. Krendler...

191
00:15:24,682 --> 00:15:27,931
out on the street, you know you might
take a bullet in the line of duty.

192
00:15:28,018 --> 00:15:30,425
You accept it, or you get out.

193
00:15:30,520 --> 00:15:32,347
You live with it.

194
00:15:32,439 --> 00:15:35,144
What you don't expect or accept...

195
00:15:35,233 --> 00:15:37,903
is taking one in the back
in your boss's office...

196
00:15:37,986 --> 00:15:40,145
for doing your job
exactly as they've taught you.

197
00:15:40,239 --> 00:15:41,899
That makes you unhappy.

198
00:15:41,990 --> 00:15:45,359
Of course you're right, Starling...

199
00:15:45,452 --> 00:15:47,445
but it doesn't change anything.

200
00:15:47,538 --> 00:15:50,741
It changes everything.
It changes me.

201
00:16:41,425 --> 00:16:44,590
Hi, I'm Cordell Doemling,
Mr Verger's private physician.

202
00:16:44,677 --> 00:16:46,255
How do you do?

203
00:16:46,345 --> 00:16:49,845
If you'd be so kind
as to park down at the end.

204
00:16:55,104 --> 00:16:57,939
One's eyes adjust to the darkness.

205
00:17:13,373 --> 00:17:16,623
Mr Verger,
Agent Starling is here.

206
00:17:16,709 --> 00:17:19,497
Good morning, Mr Verger.

207
00:17:19,587 --> 00:17:21,912
Was that a Mustang
I heard out there?

208
00:17:22,005 --> 00:17:23,120
Yes, it was.

209
00:17:23,215 --> 00:17:25,042
Five-litre?

210
00:17:25,134 --> 00:17:26,794
Yes.

211
00:17:26,885 --> 00:17:29,293
Fast.

212
00:17:29,388 --> 00:17:31,926
Cordell, I think
you can leave us now.

213
00:17:32,016 --> 00:17:36,393
I thought I might stay.
Perhaps I could be useful.

214
00:17:36,479 --> 00:17:40,690
You could be useful
seeing about my lunch.

215
00:17:45,363 --> 00:17:48,778
I'll attach this microphone to your
clothing or pillow, if that's okay.

216
00:17:48,866 --> 00:17:50,989
By all means.

217
00:17:56,123 --> 00:17:58,116
Here, this should make it easier.

218
00:18:05,882 --> 00:18:08,373
You know, I thank God...

219
00:18:08,468 --> 00:18:10,295
for what happened.

220
00:18:10,387 --> 00:18:12,545
It was my salvation.

221
00:18:13,890 --> 00:18:17,176
Have you accepted jesus,
Agent Starling?

222
00:18:17,269 --> 00:18:19,807
- Do you have faith?
- I was raised Lutheran.

223
00:18:19,897 --> 00:18:22,470
That's not what I asked.

224
00:18:22,566 --> 00:18:25,935
This is Special Agent
Clarice Starling, 51 <i>4369</i>0...

225
00:18:26,028 --> 00:18:28,863
deposing Mason R. Verger on March 20,
sworn and attested.

226
00:18:28,947 --> 00:18:31,901
I want to tell you about summer camp.
It was a wonderful childhood experience.

227
00:18:31,992 --> 00:18:34,993
- We can get to that later.
- We can get to it now.

228
00:18:35,955 --> 00:18:37,946
You see, it all comes to bear.

229
00:18:38,039 --> 00:18:42,582
It was a Christian camp
my father founded...

230
00:18:42,669 --> 00:18:47,165
for poor, unfortunate, cast-off
little boys and girls...

231
00:18:47,257 --> 00:18:50,008
who would do anything
for a candy bar.

232
00:18:50,093 --> 00:18:52,631
Mr Verger, I don't need to know
about the sex offences.

233
00:18:52,721 --> 00:18:56,172
It's all right.
I have immunity from the US Attorney.

234
00:18:56,266 --> 00:18:58,424
And I have immunity...

235
00:18:58,518 --> 00:19:01,472
from the risen jesus.

236
00:19:01,563 --> 00:19:04,101
And nobody beats the Riz.

237
00:19:04,816 --> 00:19:08,066
Had you ever seen Dr Lecter before the
court assigned you to him for therapy?

238
00:19:08,153 --> 00:19:09,528
What do you mean?

239
00:19:09,613 --> 00:19:11,404
Socially?

240
00:19:13,033 --> 00:19:16,199
It is what I mean, yes,
if you don't mind talking about it.

241
00:19:16,285 --> 00:19:18,278
No, not at all.
I'm not ashamed.

242
00:19:18,371 --> 00:19:21,621
- I didn't say you should be.
- No, we met conventionally...

243
00:19:21,707 --> 00:19:23,747
as doctor and patient.

244
00:19:23,834 --> 00:19:25,626
How did he end up at your house?

245
00:19:25,711 --> 00:19:28,629
I invited him, of course...

246
00:19:29,757 --> 00:19:32,462
<i>to my pied-�-terre.</i>

247
00:19:32,552 --> 00:19:36,715
<i>I came to the door</i>
<i>in my nicest come-hither outfit.</i>

248
00:19:36,806 --> 00:19:38,799
<i>I was concerned...</i>

249
00:19:38,891 --> 00:19:42,177
<i>that he'd be afraid of me.</i>

250
00:19:42,270 --> 00:19:45,686
<i>But he didn't seem to be</i>
<i>afraid of me.</i>

251
00:19:46,816 --> 00:19:48,939
That's almost funny now.

252
00:19:50,278 --> 00:19:52,353
<i>I showed him my toys...</i>

253
00:19:52,446 --> 00:19:55,363
<i>my noose set-up,</i>
<i>among other things.</i>

254
00:19:55,449 --> 00:19:59,696
It's where you sort of hang yourself,
but not really.

255
00:19:59,787 --> 00:20:01,910
<i>It feels good while you...</i>

256
00:20:02,790 --> 00:20:04,829
well, you know.

257
00:20:04,917 --> 00:20:06,197
Anyway...

258
00:20:06,293 --> 00:20:10,836
<i>- he said, "Mason..."</i>
- Mason, would you like a popper?

259
00:20:11,799 --> 00:20:15,298
And I said, "Would I? Oh, wow!"

260
00:20:15,386 --> 00:20:18,091
<i>Once that kicked in,</i>
<i>I was flying.</i>

261
00:20:18,180 --> 00:20:22,048
<i>He said,</i>
<i>"Mason, show me how you smile...</i>

262
00:20:22,143 --> 00:20:25,725
<i>to gain the confidence</i>
<i>of a child. "</i>

263
00:20:25,813 --> 00:20:28,767
When I smiled...

264
00:20:28,858 --> 00:20:31,774
<i>he said,</i>
<i>"Oh, I see how you do it."</i>

265
00:20:31,860 --> 00:20:36,569
<i>The good doctor approached me</i>
<i>with a piece of broken mirror.</i>

266
00:20:36,656 --> 00:20:37,736
<i>"Try this."</i>

267
00:20:38,950 --> 00:20:40,742
Try peeling off your face...

268
00:20:41,578 --> 00:20:44,283
And feeding it to the dogs.

269
00:20:53,590 --> 00:20:56,342
No, I can still see it.

270
00:20:56,426 --> 00:20:57,589
Try again.

271
00:20:58,762 --> 00:21:01,300
No, I'm afraid not.

272
00:21:01,390 --> 00:21:04,095
<i>That's entertainment</i>

273
00:21:06,270 --> 00:21:09,768
Well, it seemed like
a good idea at the time.

274
00:21:11,107 --> 00:21:14,939
You indicated to me that you'd received
some kind of new information.

275
00:21:33,296 --> 00:21:35,621
Where did this come from?

276
00:21:35,715 --> 00:21:38,835
Buenos Aires.
I received it two weeks ago.

277
00:21:40,679 --> 00:21:43,252
Where's the package it came in?

278
00:21:43,348 --> 00:21:46,846
Good question. There was nothing
written on it of interest.

279
00:21:46,934 --> 00:21:48,808
Did we throw it out?

280
00:21:49,937 --> 00:21:51,930
Yes, I'm afraid we did.

281
00:21:52,023 --> 00:21:54,774
Oh, dear.
You think it'll help?

282
00:21:54,859 --> 00:21:56,851
I hope so.

283
00:21:56,944 --> 00:21:58,937
I hope it'll help you catch him...

284
00:21:59,030 --> 00:22:03,857
to help cleanse the stigma
of your recent dishonour.

285
00:22:03,951 --> 00:22:05,611
Thank you. That's all I need.

286
00:22:05,703 --> 00:22:08,657
Did you find some rapport
with Dr Lecter...

287
00:22:08,748 --> 00:22:11,286
in your talks at the asylum?

288
00:22:12,627 --> 00:22:15,462
I know I did
while I was peeling.

289
00:22:15,546 --> 00:22:18,464
We exchanged information
in a civil way.

290
00:22:18,549 --> 00:22:21,041
But always through the glass.

291
00:22:21,135 --> 00:22:22,713
Yes.

292
00:22:32,938 --> 00:22:36,307
- Isn't it funny?
- What's that?

293
00:22:37,026 --> 00:22:39,018
You can look at my face...

294
00:22:40,362 --> 00:22:43,696
but you shied when I said
the name of God.

295
00:23:10,016 --> 00:23:13,302
- Finding what you want?
- Are you sure this is all of it?

296
00:23:13,395 --> 00:23:15,387
That's all there is now.

297
00:23:15,480 --> 00:23:18,932
There was more, but it's been picked
over little by little over the years.

298
00:23:20,444 --> 00:23:24,026
You know, this stuff's worth
a lot of money in certain circles.

299
00:23:25,699 --> 00:23:27,988
It's kind of like the cocaine
that disappears around here...

300
00:23:28,076 --> 00:23:29,452
little by little.

301
00:24:54,037 --> 00:24:55,827
Hey, Barney.

302
00:24:55,913 --> 00:24:58,285
Remember me?

303
00:24:58,373 --> 00:25:00,662
Would you agree for the record,
Agent Starling...

304
00:25:00,751 --> 00:25:02,578
that I've not been read my rights?

305
00:25:06,799 --> 00:25:11,591
I have not Mirandized Barney.
He is unaware of his rights.

306
00:25:13,305 --> 00:25:15,677
So when you turned Dr Lecter over
to the Tennessee police...

307
00:25:15,766 --> 00:25:19,846
They weren't civil to him.
They're all dead now.

308
00:25:19,937 --> 00:25:22,262
They only survived his company
three days.

309
00:25:22,356 --> 00:25:25,191
You survived him
six years at the asylum.

310
00:25:25,276 --> 00:25:28,442
How'd you do that?
It wasn't just being civil.

311
00:25:28,529 --> 00:25:31,281
Yes, it was.

312
00:25:31,365 --> 00:25:34,614
Did you ever think, after he escaped,
he might come after you?

313
00:25:34,701 --> 00:25:35,732
No.

314
00:25:35,827 --> 00:25:38,116
He once told me that,
whenever feasible...

315
00:25:38,204 --> 00:25:40,281
he preferred to eat the rude.

316
00:25:40,373 --> 00:25:44,502
"Free-range rude," he called 'em.
What about you?

317
00:25:44,586 --> 00:25:47,920
You ever think he might come after you?
You ever think about him at all?

318
00:25:48,006 --> 00:25:51,375
At least <i>3</i>0 seconds of every day.
I can't help it.

319
00:25:51,468 --> 00:25:54,339
He's always with me,
like a bad habit.

320
00:25:55,681 --> 00:25:59,595
Do you know what happened to his stuff...
his books, papers, drawings?

321
00:25:59,685 --> 00:26:02,389
Everything got thrown away
when the place closed.

322
00:26:02,479 --> 00:26:04,686
Cutbacks.

323
00:26:04,773 --> 00:26:07,976
I just found out that Dr Lecter's
signed copy of <i>TheJoy of Cooking...</i>

324
00:26:08,068 --> 00:26:11,602
sold to a private collector
for $ 1 <i>6</i>,000.

325
00:26:12,739 --> 00:26:14,897
It was probably a fake.

326
00:26:14,991 --> 00:26:18,989
The seller's affidavit of ownership
was signed "Karen Phlox."

327
00:26:19,078 --> 00:26:22,328
Do you know Karen Phlox?
You should.

328
00:26:22,415 --> 00:26:26,329
She filled out your employment
application, but signed it "Barney."

329
00:26:27,295 --> 00:26:29,537
Same thing on your tax returns.

330
00:26:32,467 --> 00:26:36,381
You want the book?
Maybe I can get it back.

331
00:26:36,471 --> 00:26:40,884
I want the X ray of Lecter's arm
you broke in the attack on that nurse...

332
00:26:40,976 --> 00:26:43,099
and everything else you've got.

333
00:26:47,065 --> 00:26:50,765
We used to talk about
a lot of things at night...

334
00:26:50,860 --> 00:26:53,730
after the screamin'
finally died down.

335
00:26:57,408 --> 00:27:01,869
We talked about you sometimes.
You wanna know what he said?

336
00:27:01,954 --> 00:27:04,196
Go get the X ray.

337
00:27:10,296 --> 00:27:12,289
I'm not a bad guy.

338
00:27:12,381 --> 00:27:13,959
I didn't say you were.

339
00:27:14,050 --> 00:27:16,541
Dr Chilton was a bad guy.

340
00:27:16,636 --> 00:27:20,847
After your first visit, he started
taping your conversations with Lecter.

341
00:27:23,267 --> 00:27:25,841
These are valuable.

342
00:27:31,275 --> 00:27:33,314
Go on now.

343
00:27:33,402 --> 00:27:35,809
You've grieved long enough.

344
00:27:40,033 --> 00:27:42,156
And what'd he say?

345
00:27:42,244 --> 00:27:44,237
What'd he say about me
late at night?

346
00:27:45,581 --> 00:27:48,451
He was talking about
inherited, hardwired behaviour.

347
00:27:48,542 --> 00:27:51,496
He was using genetics
in the roller pigeons as an example.

348
00:27:51,587 --> 00:27:56,296
They fly up in the air, roll backwards
in a display, fallin' to the ground.

349
00:27:56,383 --> 00:27:59,799
<i>There are shallow rollers,</i>
<i>and there are deep rollers.</i>

350
00:27:59,887 --> 00:28:01,880
<i>You can't breed two deep rollers...</i>

351
00:28:01,972 --> 00:28:05,175
<i>or their young, their offspring,</i>
<i>will roll all the way down...</i>

352
00:28:05,266 --> 00:28:07,555
<i>hit and die.</i>

353
00:28:07,644 --> 00:28:10,680
<i>Agent Starling is a deep roller,</i>
<i>Barney.</i>

354
00:28:10,772 --> 00:28:14,355
<i>Let us hope one of her parents</i>
<i>was not.</i>

355
00:28:14,442 --> 00:28:18,143
<i>Surely the odd confluence of events</i>
<i>hasn't escaped you, Clarice.</i>

356
00:28:19,489 --> 00:28:22,360
<i>Jack Crawford dangles you</i>
<i>in front of me...</i>

357
00:28:22,451 --> 00:28:25,155
<i>then I give you a bit of help.</i>

358
00:28:25,245 --> 00:28:27,534
<i>Do you think it's because</i>
<i>I like to look at you...</i>

359
00:28:27,622 --> 00:28:31,537
<i>and imagine how good</i>
<i>you would taste...</i>

360
00:28:31,627 --> 00:28:33,952
<i>Clarice?</i>

361
00:28:34,046 --> 00:28:36,619
<i>I don't know. Is it?</i>

362
00:28:38,800 --> 00:28:41,338
<i>I've been in this room</i>
<i>for eight years now, Clarice.</i>

363
00:28:42,137 --> 00:28:45,173
<i>I know they will never, ever</i>
<i>let me out while I'm alive.</i>

364
00:28:46,516 --> 00:28:48,639
<i>What I want is a view.</i>

365
00:28:48,726 --> 00:28:52,594
<i>I want a window where I</i>
<i>can see a tree or even water.</i>

366
00:28:52,689 --> 00:28:55,262
<i>I want to be in a federal institution</i>
<i>far away from Dr Chilton.</i>

367
00:29:09,164 --> 00:29:12,615
<i>The Capponi correspondence</i>
<i>goes back to the 13th century.</i>

368
00:29:12,709 --> 00:29:15,496
Dr Fell might hold in his hand...

369
00:29:15,587 --> 00:29:17,626
his non-Italian hand...

370
00:29:17,714 --> 00:29:20,122
a note from Dante Alighieri himself.

371
00:29:20,217 --> 00:29:23,086
But would he recognize it?
I think not.

372
00:29:24,261 --> 00:29:27,630
Gentlemen, you have examined him
in medieval Italian...

373
00:29:27,723 --> 00:29:30,345
<i>and I will not deny</i>
<i>that his language is admirable...</i>

374
00:29:30,434 --> 00:29:32,641
<i>for a</i> straniero.

375
00:29:32,728 --> 00:29:35,978
<i>But is he acquainted</i>
<i>with the personalities...</i>

376
00:29:36,065 --> 00:29:37,808
<i>of the pre-Renaissance Firenze?</i>

377
00:29:38,734 --> 00:29:40,727
I think not.

378
00:29:40,820 --> 00:29:43,489
What if he came upon a note
in the Capponi library...

379
00:29:43,573 --> 00:29:46,146
say from Guido di Cavalcanti?

380
00:29:46,242 --> 00:29:50,026
Would he recognize that?
I think not.

381
00:29:50,121 --> 00:29:52,529
They're still arguing?

382
00:29:55,376 --> 00:29:58,046
Sogliato wants the job
for his nephew.

383
00:29:58,129 --> 00:30:02,671
But the scholars seem satisfied
with the temporary guy they appointed.

384
00:30:02,758 --> 00:30:05,331
If he's such an expert on Dante...

385
00:30:05,427 --> 00:30:08,214
let him lecture on Dante
to the <i>Studiolo.</i>

386
00:30:08,305 --> 00:30:11,176
- Let him face them if he can.
- I look fo<i>rw</i>ard to it.

387
00:30:13,310 --> 00:30:15,884
Very well. On the 1 <i>4</i>th.

388
00:30:32,955 --> 00:30:35,624
Dr Fell?

389
00:30:35,708 --> 00:30:38,459
Chief Inspector Rinaldo Pazzi
of the <i>questura.</i>

390
00:30:38,626 --> 00:30:42,078
<i>Commendatore,</i>
how can I be of service?

391
00:30:42,172 --> 00:30:45,007
Sorry. I'm investigating
the disappearance...

392
00:30:45,091 --> 00:30:49,338
of your predecessor,
Signor di Bonaventura.

393
00:30:49,429 --> 00:30:52,264
- I was wondering if...
- "Predecessor" implies I have the job.

394
00:30:52,349 --> 00:30:56,049
Unfortunately, I don't.
Not yet, though I am hopeful.

395
00:30:56,144 --> 00:30:59,928
They are letting me look after
the library for a stipend.

396
00:31:01,733 --> 00:31:03,856
The officers who first checked...

397
00:31:03,944 --> 00:31:08,024
didn't find any sort of farewell
or suicide note.

398
00:31:08,115 --> 00:31:09,657
I was wondering if you...

399
00:31:09,741 --> 00:31:13,360
If I come across anything in the Capponi
library stuffed in a drawer or book...

400
00:31:13,453 --> 00:31:15,410
I'll call you at once.

401
00:31:17,498 --> 00:31:19,372
Thank you.

402
00:31:20,376 --> 00:31:22,250
You've been reassigned.

403
00:31:25,340 --> 00:31:26,502
Pardon?

404
00:31:26,591 --> 00:31:30,007
You were on the <i>II Mostro</i> case,
I'm sure I read.

405
00:31:30,094 --> 00:31:32,420
- Yes, that's right.
- Now you're on this.

406
00:31:32,513 --> 00:31:35,468
This is much less grand a case,
I would think.

407
00:31:35,558 --> 00:31:39,223
Well, if I thought of my work
in those terms...

408
00:31:39,312 --> 00:31:40,937
yes, I guess I'd agree.

409
00:31:41,689 --> 00:31:44,097
- A missing person.
- Sorry?

410
00:31:44,192 --> 00:31:48,142
Were you unfairly dismissed from
the grander case, or did you deserve it?

411
00:31:54,243 --> 00:31:56,948
Regarding this one, Dr Fell...

412
00:31:57,037 --> 00:31:59,991
are the signore's personal effects
still at the Palazzo?

413
00:32:01,625 --> 00:32:05,160
Packed neatly in four cases
with an inventory.

414
00:32:05,254 --> 00:32:07,875
Alas, no note.

415
00:32:10,468 --> 00:32:14,880
I'll send someone over to pick them up.
Thank you for your help.

416
00:32:25,691 --> 00:32:27,483
Hey, thanks.

417
00:32:29,070 --> 00:32:31,145
How's it going? Any leads?

418
00:32:31,238 --> 00:32:34,358
Yeah, they're all leads.
They just don't lead to him.

419
00:32:39,079 --> 00:32:41,072
I don't know how you live
with this stuff.

420
00:32:41,164 --> 00:32:43,620
Oh, God.

421
00:32:43,709 --> 00:32:46,330
This is from the <i>Guinness Book</i>
<i>of World Records</i> congratulating me...

422
00:32:46,420 --> 00:32:50,038
on being the female FBI agent
who has shot and killed the most people.

423
00:33:13,613 --> 00:33:15,606
Would you excuse me, please?

424
00:33:17,617 --> 00:33:19,859
Sure.

425
00:33:45,229 --> 00:33:46,686
<i>Dear Clarice...</i>

426
00:33:48,189 --> 00:33:52,234
<i>I've followed with enthusiasm the course</i>
<i>of your disgrace and public shaming.</i>

427
00:33:52,318 --> 00:33:55,604
<i>My own never bothered me</i>
<i>except for the inconvenience...</i>

428
00:33:55,696 --> 00:33:57,523
<i>of being incarcerated.</i>

429
00:33:57,615 --> 00:33:59,940
<i>But you may lack perspective.</i>

430
00:34:01,285 --> 00:34:03,408
<i>In our discussions</i>
<i>down in the dungeon...</i>

431
00:34:03,496 --> 00:34:07,328
<i>it was apparent to me that your father,</i>
<i>the dead night watchman...</i>

432
00:34:07,417 --> 00:34:09,955
<i>figures largely</i>
<i>in your value system.</i>

433
00:34:11,504 --> 00:34:15,798
<i>I think your success in putting an end</i>
<i>to Jame Gumb's career as a couturier...</i>

434
00:34:15,884 --> 00:34:20,510
<i>pleased you most because you could</i>
<i>imagine your father being pleased.</i>

435
00:34:20,597 --> 00:34:24,380
<i>But now, alas,</i>
<i>you're in bad odour with the FBI.</i>

436
00:34:24,475 --> 00:34:27,180
<i>Do you imagine your daddy</i>
<i>being shamed by your disgrace?</i>

437
00:34:27,269 --> 00:34:30,223
<i>Do you see him</i>
<i>in his plain pine box...</i>

438
00:34:30,314 --> 00:34:32,307
<i>crushed by your failure...</i>

439
00:34:32,399 --> 00:34:35,733
<i>the sorry, petty end</i>
<i>of a promising career?</i>

440
00:34:35,820 --> 00:34:39,354
<i>What is worst</i>
<i>about this humiliation, Clarice?</i>

441
00:34:39,448 --> 00:34:43,197
<i>Is it how your failure will reflect</i>
<i>on your mommy and daddy?</i>

442
00:34:44,662 --> 00:34:47,414
<i>Is your worst fear that people</i>
<i>will now and forever believe...</i>

443
00:34:47,498 --> 00:34:50,534
<i>they were indeed just good old</i>
<i>trailer-camp...</i>

444
00:34:50,626 --> 00:34:52,833
<i>tornado-bait white trash...</i>

445
00:34:52,920 --> 00:34:55,245
<i>and that perhaps you are too?</i>

446
00:34:58,426 --> 00:35:01,546
<i>By the way, I couldn't help noticing</i>
<i>on the FBI's rather dull web site...</i>

447
00:35:01,637 --> 00:35:06,512
<i>that I've been hoisted from the Bureau's</i>
<i>archives of the common criminal...</i>

448
00:35:06,600 --> 00:35:09,720
<i>and elevated to the more prestigious</i>
<i>Ten Most Wanted List.</i>

449
00:35:11,188 --> 00:35:15,399
<i>Is this coincidence,</i>
<i>or are you back on the case?</i>

450
00:35:15,484 --> 00:35:18,935
<i>If so, goody goody, because</i>
<i>I need to come out of retirement...</i>

451
00:35:19,029 --> 00:35:21,437
<i>and return to public life.</i>

452
00:35:24,743 --> 00:35:27,317
<i>I imagine you sitting</i>
<i>in a dark basement room...</i>

453
00:35:27,413 --> 00:35:30,449
<i>bent over papers</i>
<i>and computer screens.</i>

454
00:35:30,541 --> 00:35:32,580
